@node not29 "WOA IS (WAS) HERE!"

                               WOA IS (WAS) HERE!
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This is a preview of the World of Amiga written on Friday by Andrew Korn.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Friday 23rd July 1999. World of Amiga is here!

Friday  23rd  (set  up  day)  went with surprisingly few hitches and the show is
looking  very,  very nice indeed. The exhibitiors (and a few hangers - on) spent
the day getting everything ready, and it's going to be pretty special.

Amiga's  stand is, to quote Petro Tyschtschenko, "the best one yet" with a video
wall  showing a continuous programme of demonstrations and videos throughout the
day,  a  (very  lovely  looking!)  mock  up of the next generation Amiga, and of
course  copious quantities of AmiCola, Boing socks and Boing boxers. Jim Collas,
Petro,  Dr  Allan  Havemose,  Dr  Rick LeFaivre and Tom Schmidt of Amiga will be
drinking  AmiCola and chatting to showgoers throughout the weekend, but they are
far from the only attraction.

A  lot  of  new  products  are  on sale, and many more developments are on show,
including.  There  will  be  announcements  of the launch date of (amongst other
things)  Amigactive  magazine and a new NG Amiga title from Digital Illusions to
whet your appetite for the big presentation from Jim Collas and Rick LeFaivre on
Saturday  evening. We have taken delivery of two 41" screens for some incredible
big  screen  multi-player  gaming  action  in  the  arcade, where many copies of
ClickBOOM's quake guide will be given away to contestants.

Other  prizes  will  be  raffled off to show goers over the weekend, including 5
copies  of  the  4  CD  Aminet Set 8 from Weird Science and 3 fully tooled A1200
towers  from  Eyetech.  There  is a programme of how-to practical demonstrations
running throughout the weekend, and a various Amiga luminaries will be running a
fascinating seminar programme.

The  big  event  on  Friday  evening  was  a mass trip to the local Odeon to see
Phantom  Menace,  mostly visitors from European countries where the film has yet
been released. World weary and cynical locals mostly just did the sensible thing
and enjoyed a few pints around the corner. Expect to see lots of excited Germans
holding  mock  light-sabre  battles  in  the  Amiga  Exhibition Hall and lots of
bleary-eyed Brits heading upstairs or down to one of the WoA '99 bars for a hair
of the dog.

There  is  so much going on at WoA'99 that we are regretting having so much in -
there's  far  too  much  to see in just one weekend! Don't miss out on the best,
most  historic  Amiga show in years, make sure you come along if you can. If you
are  too  far  away  to  travel, you can get share some of the WoA'99 experience
through  the  weekend  long  internet  coverage  provided  through  the  UGN  at
ugn.amiga.org/events/woa99.shtml. Be there - in real life or on the 'net, but be
there, you won't want to miss this!
