@node not31 "FURTHER DEVELOPMENT OF FOUNDATION RESTORED"

                   FURTHER DEVELOPMENT OF FOUNDATION RESTORED
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Things  got  changed!  Paul Burkey visited WOA and had a discussion with another
Amiga  publishing  house  regarding  the  future  of  Foundation.  Read the full
announcement here.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Latest News, Foundation Rescued! July 25th 1999

Last  week  saw the end of Foundation development and the closure of the Support
site  due  to the ceasing of funds and the disappearance of the games publisher,
Sadeness.  At  this  years  World  of Amiga show I had a discussion with another
Amiga  publishing house regarding the future of Foundation as well as the future
of the Amiga itself. We decided that it was a shame to see Foundation fizzle out
after  such  a  short commercial shelf-life, especially when we are about to see
the Amiga make a BIG return.

Foundation will also make BIG return towards the end of 1999. This will not be a
simple  re-release of the game, it will be heavily targeted towards those people
who  bought  and enjoyed the original Foundation and it will be designed to meet
the  needs of the modern (and future) Amiga. No exact plans have been set out as
yet  (as I write this announcement the WoA is still running) but a rough list of
targets are:

   * Total rewrite in portable C++
   * 68K and PPC support (other OS/CPU options to be considered)
   * All new Levels
   * Complete in-game GUI redesign
   * Complete Graphics overhaul
   * Gameplay restructure
   * New in-game features
   * New sound and music
   * Much more!

I  don't want to make any promises I can not keep and I must stress that a short
development  time schedule dictates that I will certainly have to take care with
which new features I implement. This includes the TCP/IP mode. However, this new
publishing  deal  means  that financial support for future game development will
return  and  TCP/IP  mode would be on the top of the list for the first Updates.
The  important matter is the game-play will be restructured to make the addition
of TCP/IP more important.

Towards  the end of the year there will be a Demo released. It will be from this
Demo  that I would like you to judge the validity of the new product. It is easy
to  fill  a  web page with a list of features. Now the real hard work must begin
and I hope you enjoy the results.

More details will be announced soon including the new Publisher.
