@node not33 "WOA (BRIEF COMMENTS)"

                          WOA (BRIEF COMMENTS)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: "Keith Blakemore-Noble " <Amiga@computer.org>

Just  got  back  from  WoA,  and here's some brief comments based on some of the
presentations, and speaking to some of the exhibitors and H&P and Amiga folks...

The  show  was  not  very  busy  on  Sunday, but apparantly was rather packed on
Saturday (I'm glad I went on Sunday :) ).

CPU  -  it  will be Transmeta. Amiga are not allowed to make any annoucements to
that  effect,  and  are not allowed to make any attributable comments, but it is
Transmeta (I think we'd all guessed that already :) ).

MMC  -  to  be released by the end of this year, albeit in limited quantities to
start with.

The MMC will be in the case we've seen on the web (the case they demo'd at WoA),
although  Amiga will also be selling uncased motherboards, both to end users and
to OEMs so they can build up customised Amigas (e.g. in towers or whatever).

There  will  be a developer version released, probably a bit earlier, more about
this in a moment.

As  has been speculated and discussed here, AmigaObjects is a system designed to
run  on  a wide range of systems, ranging from computers through to DVD players,
HiFis,  TVs,  palmtops,  et  al,  all of which can communicate and appear as one
device  from teh user's point of view. (A couple of examples were given, such as
using  your PalmPilot-style computer to view TV programs, where the palmtop asks
the main system to give it the TV display, the main system identifies there is a
TV tuner in the TV and asks it for the TV video/audio which it then displays on
the palmtop. Also, imagine coming back from holiday, and being able to tell your
central  heating  system  to fire up and be ready for your return in a couple of
hours,  via  your  palmtop or some other computer, talking via the internet, for
example.  Oh  yes, and the ultimate in laziness - being able to "remote control"
your TV from half way round the world <g>).

Several  big  companies  are working with Amiga, including Corel, Adobe, Sun and
Transmeta.

Linus is working on parts of the Amiga port.

The OS wil NOT be a Linux distribution. The user suystem will have a small Linux
kernel with all the other features of OE built on top.

The  developer  system, however, will ship with as a complete Linux distribution
with the OE on top of that (to give developer tools etc).

OS3.5 is delayed by a few weeks. IF it sells well, they will carry on developing
newer  and improved versions; if it does NOT sell well, then OS3.5 is the end of
the line for the Classi OS - it's up to us :)

H&P  *WILL*  be  porting WarpUp to run on the new P5 g3 cards!!!! (This was from
H&P themselves).

IBrowse  2  is  out? Erm, no. They were selling a pre-release beta, which Hisoft
pointed out contains several bugs, which will be fixed in a free upgrade at some
point.  (A friend bought IB2, and after 5 minutes of trying it out, gave up. The
Javascript   support   is,  well,  totally  crap!  IT  seems  to  complain  that
"onmouseover"  is  not a valid JS function, for example... We haven't found a JS
page  which  it  correctly  displays  yet, but maybe there is one out there?) So
basically, they have released a beta version to coincide with WoA.

Voyager  3  pre-release  demo was also out, although they were MUCH more upfront
about it only being a pre-release demo.

No sign of AWeb 3.3 release yet.

AWeb and Miami are part of the OS3.5 distribution (although in what form was not
clarified).

Annex have a new song out.

And  that's about it. Hope this makes sense (I only posted this 'cos there's not
been much else posted here as yet...)

Oh  yes. I nearly forgot. Claim to fame time - Ben and I have the distinction of
being thrown out of the press conference by Petro himself <g>

(We  walked into the press conference, thining it was the room for Dr Havemose's
technical  presentation.  By  the  time  we  realised, it was too late to make a
graceful exit, so we lurked in a corner unobtrusivly. After a couple of moments,
Petro  came  over  and  suggested  that  we  might  be looking for the Technical
presentation in the other room. So there we have it. Not many can claim to have
been  thrown  out by Petro <g> [he was very nice and polite about it, as always,
of course] ).

Have fun, off to see Star Wars again.

TTFN,
Keith
